A: You can pass the SQLiteDatabase instance from your AdapterClass to your MainActivity. Here's how you can do it:

In your AdapterClass:

```java
public class AdapterClass {
    private SQLiteDatabase database;

    public AdapterClass(Context context, String dbName) {
        database = new DatabaseHelper(context, dbName).getWritableDatabase();
    }

    public Cursor query(String args, String[] pColumnValues) {
        return database.query(DatabaseDetail.DATABASE_TABLE, pColumnValues, args, null, null, null, null);
    }

    // other methods...
}
```

In your MainActivity:

```java
public class LoginActivity extends Activity {
    // other fields...
    private AdapterClass adapterClass;

    @Override
    protected void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) {
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);
        setContentView(R.layout.login);

        // other code...

        adapterClass = new AdapterClass(getApplicationContext(), DatabaseDetail.REGISTER);

        newUser.setOnClickListener(new View.OnClickListener() {
            @Override
            public void onClick(View v) {
                // other code...

                Cursor cursor = adapterClass.query("SELECT * FROM CUS_REGISTER WHERE CUS_NAME=? AND CUS_PHONE=?", new String[] { name, phone });
                // other code...
            }
        });
    }
}
```

In this way, you can access the SQLiteDatabase instance from your MainActivity through the AdapterClass.

Please replace "DatabaseDetail.DATABASE_TABLE" with the actual name of your database table.

Also, make sure that the database is opened before you call the query method. You can do this with the open() method of your AdapterClass.

Please note that the query method is deprecated in API 28 and higher. You should use the query method of SQLiteDatabase.

I hope this helps you to connect MainActivity class with AdapterClass.

